Shown in Fig. 2 is the rectifier. Two different rectifiers has been designed, using the same architecture, one supports higher input voltages up-to 5.5 V and the other one supports input voltage up-to 1.8 V. However, the low-voltage rectifier uses thinner gate-oxide transistors resulting in a lower threshold voltage and the minimum input voltage required for the circuit to function correctly is correspondingly lower. The difference in transistor sizes can be seen in Table 1.Fig. 3
